#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:6
msgid "Skip and xfail: dealing with tests that cannot succeed"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:8
msgid ""
"You can mark test functions that cannot be run on certain platforms or that "
"you expect to fail so pytest can deal with them accordingly and present a "
"summary of the test session, while keeping the test suite *green*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:12
msgid ""
"A **skip** means that you expect your test to pass only if some conditions "
"are met, otherwise pytest should skip running the test altogether. Common "
"examples are skipping windows-only tests on non-windows platforms, or "
"skipping tests that depend on an external resource which is not available at "
"the moment (for example a database)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:17
msgid ""
"A **xfail** means that you expect a test to fail for some reason. A common "
"example is a test for a feature not yet implemented, or a bug not yet fixed. "
"When a test passes despite being expected to fail (marked with ``pytest.mark."
"xfail``), it's an **xpass** and will be reported in the test summary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:22
msgid ""
"``pytest`` counts and lists *skip* and *xfail* tests separately. Detailed "
"information about skipped/xfailed tests is not shown by default to avoid "
"cluttering the output.  You can use the ``-r`` option to see details "
"corresponding to the \"short\" letters shown in the test progress:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:27
msgid "pytest -rxXs  # show extra info on xfailed, xpassed, and skipped tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:31
msgid ""
"More details on the ``-r`` option can be found by running ``pytest -h``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:33
msgid "(See :ref:`how to change command line options defaults`)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:40
msgid "Skipping test functions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:44
msgid ""
"The simplest way to skip a test function is to mark it with the ``skip`` "
"decorator which may be passed an optional ``reason``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:47
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.skip(reason=\"no way of currently testing this\")\n"
"def test_the_unknown():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:54
msgid ""
"Alternatively, it is also possible to skip imperatively during test "
"execution or setup by calling the ``pytest.skip(reason)`` function:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:57
msgid ""
"def test_function():\n"
"    if not valid_config():\n"
"        pytest.skip(\"unsupported configuration\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:63
msgid ""
"The imperative method is useful when it is not possible to evaluate the skip "
"condition during import time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:66
msgid ""
"It is also possible to skip the whole module using ``pytest.skip(reason, "
"allow_module_level=True)`` at the module level:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:69
msgid ""
"import sys\n"
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"if not sys.platform.startswith(\"win\"):\n"
"    pytest.skip(\"skipping windows-only tests\", allow_module_level=True)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:78
msgid "**Reference**: :ref:`pytest.mark.skip ref`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:81
msgid "``skipif``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:85
msgid ""
"If you wish to skip something conditionally then you can use ``skipif`` "
"instead. Here is an example of marking a test function to be skipped when "
"run on an interpreter earlier than Python3.6:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:89
msgid ""
"import sys\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.skipif(sys.version_info < (3, 6), reason=\"requires python3.6 "
"or higher\")\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:98
msgid ""
"If the condition evaluates to ``True`` during collection, the test function "
"will be skipped, with the specified reason appearing in the summary when "
"using ``-rs``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:101
msgid ""
"You can share ``skipif`` markers between modules.  Consider this test module:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:103
msgid ""
"# content of test_mymodule.py\n"
"import mymodule\n"
"\n"
"minversion = pytest.mark.skipif(\n"
"    mymodule.__versioninfo__ < (1, 1), reason=\"at least mymodule-1.1 "
"required\"\n"
")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@minversion\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:117
msgid "You can import the marker and reuse it in another test module:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:119
msgid ""
"# test_myothermodule.py\n"
"from test_mymodule import minversion\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@minversion\n"
"def test_anotherfunction():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:129
msgid ""
"For larger test suites it's usually a good idea to have one file where you "
"define the markers which you then consistently apply throughout your test "
"suite."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:133
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can use :ref:`condition strings <string conditions>` "
"instead of booleans, but they can't be shared between modules easily so they "
"are supported mainly for backward compatibility reasons."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:137
msgid "**Reference**: :ref:`pytest.mark.skipif ref`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:141
msgid "Skip all test functions of a class or module"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:143
msgid "You can use the ``skipif`` marker (as any other marker) on classes:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:145
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.skipif(sys.platform == \"win32\", reason=\"does not run on "
"windows\")\n"
"class TestPosixCalls:\n"
"    def test_function(self):\n"
"        \"will not be setup or run under 'win32' platform\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:152
msgid ""
"If the condition is ``True``, this marker will produce a skip result for "
"each of the test methods of that class."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:155
msgid ""
"If you want to skip all test functions of a module, you may use the "
"``pytestmark`` name on the global level:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:158
msgid ""
"# test_module.py\n"
"pytestmark = pytest.mark.skipif(...)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:163
msgid ""
"If multiple ``skipif`` decorators are applied to a test function, it will be "
"skipped if any of the skip conditions is true."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:170
msgid "Skipping files or directories"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:172
msgid ""
"Sometimes you may need to skip an entire file or directory, for example if "
"the tests rely on Python version-specific features or contain code that you "
"do not wish pytest to run. In this case, you must exclude the files and "
"directories from collection. Refer to :ref:`customizing-test-collection` for "
"more information."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:180
msgid "Skipping on a missing import dependency"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:182
msgid ""
"You can skip tests on a missing import by using :ref:`pytest.importorskip "
"ref` at module level, within a test, or test setup function."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:185
msgid "docutils = pytest.importorskip(\"docutils\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:189
msgid ""
"If ``docutils`` cannot be imported here, this will lead to a skip outcome of "
"the test. You can also skip based on the version number of a library:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:192
msgid "docutils = pytest.importorskip(\"docutils\", minversion=\"0.3\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:196
msgid ""
"The version will be read from the specified module's ``__version__`` "
"attribute."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:200
msgid "Summary"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:202
msgid ""
"Here's a quick guide on how to skip tests in a module in different "
"situations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:204
msgid "Skip all tests in a module unconditionally:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:206
msgid "pytestmark = pytest.mark.skip(\"all tests still WIP\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:210
msgid "Skip all tests in a module based on some condition:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:212
msgid ""
"pytestmark = pytest.mark.skipif(sys.platform == \"win32\", reason=\"tests "
"for linux only\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:216
msgid "Skip all tests in a module if some import is missing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:218
msgid "pexpect = pytest.importorskip(\"pexpect\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:226
msgid "XFail: mark test functions as expected to fail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:228
msgid ""
"You can use the ``xfail`` marker to indicate that you expect a test to fail:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:231
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.xfail\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:237
msgid ""
"This test will run but no traceback will be reported when it fails. Instead, "
"terminal reporting will list it in the \"expected to fail\" (``XFAIL``) or "
"\"unexpectedly passing\" (``XPASS``) sections."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:241
msgid ""
"Alternatively, you can also mark a test as ``XFAIL`` from within the test or "
"its setup function imperatively:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:244
msgid ""
"def test_function():\n"
"    if not valid_config():\n"
"        pytest.xfail(\"failing configuration (but should work)\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:250
msgid ""
"def test_function2():\n"
"    import slow_module\n"
"\n"
"    if slow_module.slow_function():\n"
"        pytest.xfail(\"slow_module taking too long\")"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:258
msgid ""
"These two examples illustrate situations where you don't want to check for a "
"condition at the module level, which is when a condition would otherwise be "
"evaluated for marks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:261
msgid ""
"This will make ``test_function`` ``XFAIL``. Note that no other code is "
"executed after the ``pytest.xfail`` call, differently from the marker. "
"That's because it is implemented internally by raising a known exception."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:265
msgid "**Reference**: :ref:`pytest.mark.xfail ref`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:271
msgid "``strict`` parameter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:275
msgid ""
"Both ``XFAIL`` and ``XPASS`` don't fail the test suite by default. You can "
"change this by setting the ``strict`` keyword-only parameter to ``True``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:278
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.xfail(strict=True)\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:285
msgid ""
"This will make ``XPASS`` (\"unexpectedly passing\") results from this test "
"to fail the test suite."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:287
msgid ""
"You can change the default value of the ``strict`` parameter using the "
"``xfail_strict`` ini option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:290
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"xfail_strict=true"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:297
msgid "``reason`` parameter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:299
msgid ""
"As with skipif_ you can also mark your expectation of a failure on a "
"particular platform:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:302
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.xfail(sys.version_info >= (3, 6), reason=\"python3.6 api "
"changes\")\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:310
msgid "``raises`` parameter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:312
msgid ""
"If you want to be more specific as to why the test is failing, you can "
"specify a single exception, or a tuple of exceptions, in the ``raises`` "
"argument."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:315
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.xfail(raises=RuntimeError)\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:321
msgid ""
"Then the test will be reported as a regular failure if it fails with an "
"exception not mentioned in ``raises``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:325
msgid "``run`` parameter"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:327
msgid ""
"If a test should be marked as xfail and reported as such but should not be "
"even executed, use the ``run`` parameter as ``False``:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:330
msgid ""
"@pytest.mark.xfail(run=False)\n"
"def test_function():\n"
"    ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:336
msgid ""
"This is specially useful for xfailing tests that are crashing the "
"interpreter and should be investigated later."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:341
msgid "Ignoring xfail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:343
msgid "By specifying on the commandline:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:345
msgid "pytest --runxfail"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:349
msgid ""
"you can force the running and reporting of an ``xfail`` marked test as if it "
"weren't marked at all. This also causes ``pytest.xfail`` to produce no "
"effect."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:353
msgid "Examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:355
msgid "Here is a simple test file with the several usages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:357
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"xfail = pytest.mark.xfail\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@xfail\n"
"def test_hello():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@xfail(run=False)\n"
"def test_hello2():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@xfail(\"hasattr(os, 'sep')\")\n"
"def test_hello3():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@xfail(reason=\"bug 110\")\n"
"def test_hello4():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@xfail('pytest.__version__[0] != \"17\"')\n"
"def test_hello5():\n"
"    assert 0\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"def test_hello6():\n"
"    pytest.xfail(\"reason\")\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@xfail(raises=IndexError)\n"
"def test_hello7():\n"
"    x = []\n"
"    x[1] = 1\n"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:359
msgid "Running it with the report-on-xfail option gives this output:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:361
msgid ""
"example $ pytest -rx xfail_demo.py\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-5.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR/example\n"
"collected 7 items\n"
"\n"
"xfail_demo.py xxxxxxx                                                [100%]\n"
"\n"
"========================= short test summary info "
"==========================\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello2\n"
"  reason: [NOTRUN]\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello3\n"
"  condition: hasattr(os, 'sep')\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello4\n"
"  bug 110\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello5\n"
"  condition: pytest.__version__[0] != \"17\"\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello6\n"
"  reason: reason\n"
"XFAIL xfail_demo.py::test_hello7\n"
"============================ 7 xfailed in 0.12s ============================"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:390
msgid "Skip/xfail with parametrize"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:392
msgid ""
"It is possible to apply markers like skip and xfail to individual test "
"instances when using parametrize:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/skipping.rst:395
msgid ""
"import pytest\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.mark.parametrize(\n"
"    (\"n\", \"expected\"),\n"
"    [\n"
"        (1, 2),\n"
"        pytest.param(1, 0, marks=pytest.mark.xfail),\n"
"        pytest.param(1, 3, marks=pytest.mark.xfail(reason=\"some bug\")),\n"
"        (2, 3),\n"
"        (3, 4),\n"
"        (4, 5),\n"
"        pytest.param(\n"
"            10, 11, marks=pytest.mark.skipif(sys.version_info >= (3, 0), "
"reason=\"py2k\")\n"
"        ),\n"
"    ],\n"
")\n"
"def test_increment(n, expected):\n"
"    assert n + 1 == expected"
msgstr ""
